:R-HSA-9018681  a           owl:NamedIndividual , obo:GO_0042759 ;
        rdfs:comment        "Docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), a major ω-3 polyunsaturated fatty acid (PUFA) found in fish oil is the source of protectins (PDs), one of the specialized proresolving mediators (SPMs) that show potent anti-inflammatory and pro-resolving actions (Molfino et al. 2017, Balas & Durand 2016). The switch from synthesis of pro-inflammatory eicosanoids, such as the prostaglandins and the thromboxanes, to the pro-resolving lipoxins, resolvins and protectins, occurs via induction of the 15-lipoxygenase enzyme.<br><br>Protectin, identified as (N)PD1 (N signifies neuroprotectin when produced in neural tissues) is derived from DHA through the actions of 15-lipoxygenase then enzymatic hydrolysis. Aspirin can also trigger the formation of epimeric protectin (AT-PD1) (Serhan et al. 2015). An additional protectin (DX) is formed through the sequential actions of two lipoxygenase reactions. The biosynthesis of these protectins is described here (Balas & Durand 2016, Balas et al. 2014, Serhan et al. 2014, Serhan et al. 2015)." ;
        rdfs:label          "Biosynthesis of protectins" ;
        dc:contributor      "Reviewed: Hansen, Trond Vidar, 2018-02-21" , "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Authored: Jassal, Bijay, 2017-09-04" , "Edited: Jassal, Bijay, 2017-09-04" ;
        dc:date             "2026-06-29" ;
        pav:providedBy      "https://reactome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "R-HSA-9018681" ;
        skos:narrower       <http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-9018677/R-HSA-9018677> ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

